match_context.values: @{Product=Microsoft Windows Operating System; CurrentDirectory=C:\Users\george\Desktop\; OriginalFileName=sysinfo.exe; Hashes=MD5=4B3438B4516FA9CA1E49B2ABA634472C,SHA256=0984C8EA65CB17E8E41EFDBFAA525098C12979B0DCCA49928C11DD069DDB0028,IMPHASH=4E384B85600C32FD4255E59E38963F81; Description=Displays system information; FileVersion=10.0.17134.1 (WinBuild.160101.0800); ParentCommandLine=C:\Windows\system32\cmd.exe /c C:\Users\george\AppData\Local\Temp\a.bat; CommandLine=systeminfo  ; EventID=1; ParentImage=C:\Windows\SysWOW64\cmd.exe; IntegrityLevel=High; Image=C:\Windows\SysWOW64\systeminfo.exe; Company=Microsoft Corporation}

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The sample exhibits clear backdoor and downloader functionality. Key malicious behaviors include: 1) System reconnaissance via sub_402210, which creates a batch file ('a.bat') to aggregate systeminfo, tasklist, and directory structures into a temporary file. 2) Privilege escalation attempts in sub_402470 by enabling 'SeDebugPrivilege'. 3) C2 communication with 'followgho.byethost7.com' using custom HTTP headers and User-Agents to exfiltrate data via POST requests to 'host/post.php'. 4) Payload delivery in sub_402620, where it downloads an encrypted binary ('netstate.dll') from 'host/download.php', decrypts it using a bitwise NOT operation, and executes it via LoadLibraryA. The presence of the 'GHOST419' identifier suggests a variant of the Gh0st RAT or a similar malware family.
